h-century Philadelphia, where most African Americans were free, enacted a kind of rehearsal for the national emancipation that followed in the post-Civil War years. She explores the lives of the “regular” women of antebellum Philadelphia, the free black institutions that took root there, and the previously unrecognized importance of African American women to the history of American cities.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aAfrican American womenzPennsylvaniazPhiladelphiaxHistoryy19th century. 0aAfrican American womenzPennsylvaniazPhiladelphiaxSocial conditionsy19th century. 0aAntislavery movementszPennsylvaniazPhiladelphiaxHistoryy19th century. 0aEnslaved personsxEmancipationzPennsylvaniazPhiladelphiaxHistory. 0aFree African AmericanszPennsylvaniazPhiladelphiaxHistoryy19th century. 0aFree African AmericanszPennsylvaniazPhiladelphiaxSocial conditionsy19th century. 0aSlaveryzPennsylvaniazPennsylvaniazPhiladelphiaxHistory. 0aSlavesxEmancipationzPennsylvaniazPhiladelphiaxHistory. 7aHISTORY / United States / 19th Century.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831105379940 cprintz978030012591740uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/978030014506940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300145069423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300145069/original  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY